{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650459"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:11:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:11:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18401"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114258"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11119"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10382"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25777"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114258"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding the motor cortex and movements?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fine movements take more cortical space than gross movements","Motor cortex has inputs from a single brain region","Conscious movement is controlled by the sensory cortex","Gross movements require more cortical space than fine movements","The motor cortex is not involved in voluntary movement"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe motor cortex is responsible for the planning, control, and execution of voluntary movements. It is organised somatotopically, meaning different regions of the motor cortex correspond to different parts of the body. \u003Cstrong\u003EFine movements take more cortical space than gross movements\u003C/strong\u003E because they require more precise control and coordination. This is why areas like the hands and face, which perform intricate tasks, have larger representations in the motor cortex compared to areas responsible for gross movements like the trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emotor cortex has inputs from a single brain region\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the motor cortex receives inputs from multiple brain regions, including the sensory cortex, basal ganglia, and cerebellum, which help integrate sensory information and coordinate movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConscious movement is controlled by the sensory cortex\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as conscious movement is controlled by the motor cortex, not the sensory cortex, which is primarily involved in processing sensory information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGross movements require more cortical space than fine movements\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as they are less complex and require less precise control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe motor cortex is not involved in voluntary movement\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the motor cortex is indeed involved in voluntary movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The motor cortex is responsible for planning, controlling, and executing voluntary movements.","Fine motor movements require more cortical space than gross movements due to the need for precise control.","The motor cortex receives inputs from multiple brain regions, including the sensory cortex and basal ganglia."],"references":["Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 56; pg. 697."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:22:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:22:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11119"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114258"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}